            <h1>Unpaid Tolls and Violations</h1>

            <h2>What's the difference?</h2>
            <p><b>Unpaid Tolls:</b> When a driver finds himself on the Toll Road with no cash (and no EZ TAG), he will be required at the toll collection booths to fill out an Unpaid Toll form.  Currently, we do not offer online payment for Unpaid Tolls (UPTs). If you received a UPT at a collector attended lane, please use the form that you received to mail in payment.</p>

            <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/meta/media/violations/unpaid-thumbnail.gif" width="350px" height="150px" alt="" />

            <p>If you did not receive the form or have misplaced it, please make a check payable to Harris County and mail it to:</p>
            <p align="center">Harris County Toll Road Authority<br>
              Unpaid Tolls<br>
              P.O. Box 4440<br>
              Dept.03<br>
              Houston, Texas 77210-4440</p>
            <p>Please be sure to include with the check your vehicle's license plate number along with the approximate time, date, and location of the UPT.
            </p>
            
            <p><b>Violation Invoices:</b> When a vehicle passes through our EZ TAG readers and we can't collect the tolls from an EZ Account (either because the vehicle is not associated with an EZ Account, or because it is associated with a suspended EZ Account)-that's a violation.  When the license plate number doesn't match up with a valid EZ Account, we then have to expend resources to find and invoice the registered owner of that vehicle.  A "Toll Violation Invoice" will require payment of the tolls owed, plus administrative fees.</p>
            
<p><a href="#close" onclick="javascript:window.close();return false;">Close</a></p>
